   <titles>
      <title>Orthogonal Vector Decomposition - Explanation</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>The proposition on orthogonal vector decomposition says that given subspaces <math>
                     <latex>V\subseteq W</latex>
                  </math> of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                  </math>, every <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> has a unique sum expression</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.array column="3">
               <row rowspan="1">
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <text>=</text>
                  </cell>
                  <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                     <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}_V + \Vect{x}_{\bot}</latex>
                     </math>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </math.array>
            <para>
               <para.body>where <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}_V=\pr_V(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math> is in <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}_{\bot}:= \Vect{x}- \pr_V(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math> is in <math>
                     <latex>V^{\bot}</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>Let us express in words what this proposition says: given an arbitrary <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math>, there are two uniquely determined vectors <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}_V</latex>
                  </math> and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}_{\bot}</latex>
                  </math> satisfying the following two conditions</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}_V</latex>
                        </math> is in <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math> and is computed as the orthogonal projection <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}_V := \pr_V(\Vect{x})</latex>
                        </math> of <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                        </math> onto <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Vect{x}_{\bot}</latex>
                        </math> belongs to the orthogonal complement of <math>
                           <latex>V</latex>
                        </math> in <math>
                           <latex>W</latex>
                        </math>. It is computed as</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.array column="3">
                     <row rowspan="1">
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x}_{\bot}</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <text>=</text>
                        </cell>
                        <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                           <math>
                              <latex>\Vect{x} - \pr_V(\Vect{x})</latex>
                           </math>
                        </cell>
                     </row>
                  </math.array>
               </li>
            </ol>
            <para>
               <para.body>As a consequence, <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{x}_V + \Vect{x}_{\bot}</latex>
                  </math> has been ‘split’ into the sum of <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}_V</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>V</latex>
                  </math>, and <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}_{\bot}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>V^{\bot}</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
